      {
        "id": "https://openalex.org/W7168129961",
        "doi": "10.1016/j.measurement.2026.122564",
        "title": "Comparative analysis of shearlet and wavelet transforms for vibro-acoustography image enhancement",
        "published": "2026-07-13",
        "url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.measurement.2026.122564",
        "authors": [
          "Bruno Silva Marció",
          "Artur Antonio Seibert",
          "Rodolfo C.C. Flesch"
        ],
        "institutions": [
          "Universidade Federal de Mato Grosso",
          "Universidade Federal de Santa Catarina"
        ],
        "journal": "Measurement",
        "abstract": "Despite being a powerful nondestructive inspection technique, vibro-acoustography (VA) suffers from image quality issues caused by intense wave reverberation artifacts. This phenomenon manifests as bright and dark fringes, resulting in a highly anisotropic and heterogeneous image background. This paper proposes a shearlet transform-based method designed to mitigate these intense fringes while preserving defect characteristics in VA images. Experimental tests were conducted on a metal sample with machined circular defects that presented different sizes and shapes. For comparison purposes, the images generated by the proposed shearlet method were evaluated with those processed using a two-level fourth-order Daubechies wavelet approach. Both qualitative and quantitative analyses were conducted to evaluate their performance, and the results confirmed that both shearlet and wavelet methods significantly reduced reverberation artifacts in the original VA images. Regarding the qualitative analysis, while the wavelet approach achieved considerable artifact reduction, resulting in images with a more uniform background, it also compromised the characterization of the defects. In contrast, the shearlet method provided superior performance in preserving the contours of the machined defects, despite its less intense artifact attenuation. Further quantitative assessment supported these observations. The wavelet method demonstrated superior artifact attenuation and background uniformity, reducing the standard deviation of pixel intensities in background areas from the original VA image by up to approximately 50%. However, for defect feature preservation, the shearlet method demonstrated significantly higher peak signal-to-noise ratio values, (e.g., reaching approximately double the values of the wavelet approach), thus proving more robust in maintaining the integrity of defect characteristics.",
        "citation_count": 0,
        "method": "Experimental"
